1
00:00:04,217 --> 00:00:07,978
Hello everybody, welcome to the Independent Games Summit.

2
00:00:08,299 --> 00:00:16,543
I am happy to introduce Tomas Grip, directly from Sweden, and he's going to tell us about

3
00:00:16,643 --> 00:00:17,443
Amnesia and...

4
00:00:18,624 --> 00:00:19,524
Mostly Amnesia, I guess.

5
00:00:19,724 --> 00:00:19,944
Yes.

6
00:00:20,204 --> 00:00:20,404
Okay.

7
00:00:21,905 --> 00:00:23,806
Yeah, so, hi everybody.

8
00:00:24,006 --> 00:00:30,849
So as has been said, I am Tomas Grip, and I'm one of the founders of Frictional Games.

9
00:00:31,637 --> 00:00:36,080
For ten years now I've been working on various horror game projects.

10
00:00:36,120 --> 00:00:43,726
The first five I've mainly done homebrew stuff and for the last five I've been involved in

11
00:00:43,766 --> 00:00:45,147
various commercial projects.

12
00:00:45,807 --> 00:00:51,811
These commercial projects include games such as the Pramana series and now most recently

13
00:00:51,891 --> 00:00:56,555
Amnesia the Dark Descent, which is the game that this lecture will sort of focus on.

14
00:00:57,784 --> 00:01:03,585
Now, the reason why I'm so interested in horror games is because it's one of the only genres

15
00:01:03,806 --> 00:01:07,586
in games that focus on evoking emotions.

16
00:01:07,646 --> 00:01:10,487
It's perhaps the only genre in games that does this.

17
00:01:10,847 --> 00:01:17,389
Even commercial projects, they can throw away more normal game stuff that you have in order

18
00:01:17,449 --> 00:01:20,550
to get close into this horror atmosphere.

19
00:01:20,970 --> 00:01:25,211
And horror games is not really even a gameplay style, genre.

20
00:01:26,731 --> 00:01:30,294
Most of the horror games you see are action-adventure type of affairs,

21
00:01:30,434 --> 00:01:34,677
but I don't see any problem with a strategy game being a horror game

22
00:01:34,997 --> 00:01:38,919
as long as you have this kind of horror response to it.

23
00:01:39,520 --> 00:01:45,043
Now, this focus on evoking emotion is something that has been very evident

24
00:01:45,163 --> 00:01:48,326
in the development of Amnesia, The Dark Descent.

25
00:01:49,724 --> 00:01:55,366
And we had to have this really strict goal that we should have a strong horror emotion,

26
00:01:55,526 --> 00:01:57,907
more than in any other game we have made before.

27
00:01:58,328 --> 00:02:03,990
And because of this, I think that Amnesia is very well the best game we have made so far.

28
00:02:04,050 --> 00:02:09,732
And press response that we have had for the game seems to confirm this.

29
00:02:10,212 --> 00:02:12,033
For example, Rock Paper Shotgun says,

30
00:02:12,113 --> 00:02:17,295
I think it's safe to say that Amnesia is the most successfully frightening game to have been made.

31
00:02:18,256 --> 00:02:23,381
And the game informer says if Resident Evil is alien, Amnesia is alien.

32
00:02:24,834 --> 00:02:32,160
And we have also, apart from getting these good words from people, we have sold over 400,000 units.

33
00:02:32,800 --> 00:02:39,946
And this is without any real PR. We have only relied on word of mouth and the press response, as you just saw.

34
00:02:40,266 --> 00:02:43,109
And this is for a niche game, like a horror game.

35
00:02:43,629 --> 00:02:49,634
And on top of all this, we have actually gotten quite the reputation of being THE scary game.

36
00:02:49,934 --> 00:02:51,856
Now, here's some example from the Internet.

37
00:02:52,176 --> 00:02:54,158
Here you have the scared pug.

38
00:02:55,679 --> 00:02:59,601
Someone who played Amnesia Dark Descent for five minutes and okay, that's close enough.

39
00:03:00,622 --> 00:03:05,484
Here's someone who drew themselves during one of the scenes in our game.

40
00:03:06,224 --> 00:03:10,586
Now, having this kind of response is really, really great.

41
00:03:10,626 --> 00:03:14,448
We're really overwhelmed with the response that we have had from this.

42
00:03:14,888 --> 00:03:17,430
Now, you can ask, why this success?

43
00:03:17,910 --> 00:03:20,571
Why is Amnesia considered such a scary game?

44
00:03:20,751 --> 00:03:22,512
Now, I think this boils down to...

45
00:03:22,932 --> 00:03:24,394
three main principles.

46
00:03:24,574 --> 00:03:27,457
And during this lecture, I will go over these main principles

47
00:03:27,557 --> 00:03:29,859
and discuss them and how they came about.

48
00:03:30,200 --> 00:03:32,282
And then I will also dig a little bit deeper

49
00:03:32,322 --> 00:03:34,904
and discuss what do these principles mean,

50
00:03:34,944 --> 00:03:39,749
what they can tell us about game design in general.

51
00:03:40,690 --> 00:03:42,412
Now, for the first part,

52
00:03:42,912 --> 00:03:44,975
where I just talk about the different decisions.

53
00:03:46,775 --> 00:03:51,076
So, the first design principle is not to use any weapons.

54
00:03:51,136 --> 00:03:56,397
In Amnesia, pretty much what the player does is either to hide or to run away from the

55
00:03:56,437 --> 00:03:57,678
monsters they encounter.

56
00:03:58,358 --> 00:04:01,239
This decision has a bit of a history to it.

57
00:04:01,299 --> 00:04:07,600
It all started out with that game, the Penumbra Tech demo, that we did in 2006, when frictional

58
00:04:07,640 --> 00:04:09,061
games really didn't exist.

59
00:04:10,351 --> 00:04:13,993
a bit due to design, but I guess mainly due to a lack of resources.

60
00:04:14,033 --> 00:04:15,693
We didn't have any combat in that game.

61
00:04:16,173 --> 00:04:21,796
Now, when we started our first commercial game, Penumbra Overture, overwhelming player

62
00:04:21,836 --> 00:04:24,157
response said, you must have weapons in your game.

63
00:04:24,517 --> 00:04:26,658
So we thought, this makes sense.

64
00:04:27,058 --> 00:04:33,301
It's a very common horror trope that the protagonist has as a last line of defense, picks up whatever

65
00:04:33,321 --> 00:04:38,643
is around and use that to fend the enemy or the monsters or whatever away.

66
00:04:39,624 --> 00:04:44,845
And this is really interesting, so we thought that yeah, we must have this.

67
00:04:44,925 --> 00:04:49,926
And in Penumbra Tech Demo, what happened was that the player found all this stuff flying

68
00:04:49,986 --> 00:04:54,428
around and they can imagine themselves, oh I can pick this up and use that as a weapon.

69
00:04:54,708 --> 00:04:59,489
And we thought, okay, if you can't pick it up, then it might break the immersion of the

70
00:04:59,529 --> 00:04:59,869
game.

71
00:05:00,309 --> 00:05:03,970
So we made a combat system for Penumbra Overture.

72
00:05:04,631 --> 00:05:10,682
made it intentionally quite clumsy. Our intent was that the player should just hit an enemy

73
00:05:10,702 --> 00:05:14,629
and then run off and wait until the danger was over.

74
00:05:15,671 --> 00:05:22,594
Now, the arsenal for Penumbra Overture, it had stuff like a pretty clumsy pickaxe, a

75
00:05:22,674 --> 00:05:26,235
hammer, and a broom.

76
00:05:26,355 --> 00:05:31,198
So we went to great lengths to make sure that the weapons were not very practical.

77
00:05:31,518 --> 00:05:36,100
And on top of this, we never called them weapons items, we called them tools.

78
00:05:36,300 --> 00:05:43,143
So we made all this, we had this clumsy combat system, we had these non-practical weapons

79
00:05:46,044 --> 00:05:48,365
We had this vague naming, as I said, and we thought,

80
00:05:48,465 --> 00:05:51,286
OK, we're set, we're going to emulate this last line of defense.

81
00:05:51,986 --> 00:05:52,627
We were wrong.

82
00:05:52,647 --> 00:05:57,649
It turns out, when the player has an opportunity to kill something, they will.

83
00:05:57,669 --> 00:06:03,532
If only armed with a puny little hammer and you have this huge demonic dog charging them,

84
00:06:03,812 --> 00:06:09,034
the player will just go to straight attack and try and bash the brains out of this dog.

85
00:06:09,294 --> 00:06:11,355
And now, of course, two things will happen here.

86
00:06:12,015 --> 00:06:15,737
Either the player will find some ingenious way to abuse our system,

87
00:06:15,937 --> 00:06:18,038
killing the enemy quite easily,

88
00:06:18,259 --> 00:06:21,020
and then because of this, the scariness factor goes down.

89
00:06:21,720 --> 00:06:24,722
Or the other thing that happens is that the player will just treat it

90
00:06:24,802 --> 00:06:27,403
as your normal first-person hack and slash,

91
00:06:27,903 --> 00:06:30,425
go ahead with that, and then die horribly,

92
00:06:30,685 --> 00:06:31,585
of course thinking that,

93
00:06:31,945 --> 00:06:35,927
oh God, the combat sucked in this game, and the game sucks.

94
00:06:36,568 --> 00:06:40,950
And so, only a minority did what we thought they would do.

95
00:06:41,130 --> 00:06:41,250
So...

96
00:06:42,371 --> 00:06:51,561
The combat was failed. Now, for our next game, the follow up for Penumbra Overture Black Plague, we thought we had to mend this somehow, but how to make it work?

97
00:06:52,121 --> 00:06:56,686
The obvious thing would be, okay, Alexios fixed the combat, and we talked about this a bit.

98
00:06:57,287 --> 00:07:02,112
we can add some circle-strafing like in Zelda, or let's just, we had this mouse control,

99
00:07:02,132 --> 00:07:03,733
let's remove the mouse control.

100
00:07:04,073 --> 00:07:06,836
But the more we discuss this, we just realize that

101
00:07:07,196 --> 00:07:09,919
this is just gonna make the game into a hack and slash,

102
00:07:09,979 --> 00:07:12,362
and that's not really what we want the game to be.

103
00:07:12,422 --> 00:07:15,985
So this time, we'll remove the weapons from the game,

104
00:07:16,506 --> 00:07:20,549
and this time, not due to lack of resources, but as a design choice.

105
00:07:21,678 --> 00:07:27,680
But now, with Combat Gun, players approach the game quite differently.

106
00:07:28,460 --> 00:07:34,422
The enemies were seen as more frightening, and players started to notice other experience-wise

107
00:07:34,942 --> 00:07:36,343
more important things.

108
00:07:36,443 --> 00:07:42,125
So not only was the whole combat or the enemy encounters changed, but they changed their

109
00:07:42,185 --> 00:07:47,686
entire look at the game, and this was quite a revelation for us, even so.

110
00:07:48,407 --> 00:07:50,868
the lure of having combat, it's quite strong.

111
00:07:51,008 --> 00:07:52,628
So for Amnesia, of course, we thought,

112
00:07:52,728 --> 00:07:55,129
okay, let's do a combat system for Amnesia.

113
00:07:55,429 --> 00:07:57,230
So we added a combat system,

114
00:07:57,570 --> 00:07:59,231
and then once again, we failed with it.

115
00:07:59,651 --> 00:08:02,232
It was just too hard to balance it

116
00:08:02,272 --> 00:08:04,273
without getting this kind of response

117
00:08:04,313 --> 00:08:05,373
that we had in Overture.

118
00:08:05,993 --> 00:08:08,054
So I will talk a little bit later on

119
00:08:08,234 --> 00:08:11,315
why this lure of having combat is so strong,

120
00:08:11,355 --> 00:08:13,216
and also when you remove combat,

121
00:08:13,276 --> 00:08:16,157
why the game changes in very drastic ways.

122
00:08:17,047 --> 00:08:19,790
Now, for the next thing. No death.

123
00:08:20,491 --> 00:08:24,115
So, this may sound a bit weird for a horror game.

124
00:08:24,135 --> 00:08:32,365
Other titles in the genre have gone to great lengths to make sure that dying is really, really bad.

125
00:08:32,405 --> 00:08:34,408
You have Resident Evil, who have this...

126
00:08:35,629 --> 00:08:40,651
their ink ribbons in order to make sure that the player doesn't save it often.

127
00:08:40,671 --> 00:08:45,633
You have forbidden siren that uses, you have to repeat the entire levels.

128
00:08:46,093 --> 00:08:52,396
Now intuitively it might seem that, okay, if we have a strong penalty for the player

129
00:08:52,576 --> 00:08:57,638
whenever they die, whenever they're in a situation where they think they're going to die, they

130
00:08:57,698 --> 00:08:59,279
feel like a lot is at stake.

131
00:08:59,479 --> 00:09:04,881
Now I do agree that this is true, but only to a certain extent.

132
00:09:06,156 --> 00:09:12,098
The first time when we started thinking about this no-death thing came about with chase sequences.

133
00:09:12,438 --> 00:09:17,359
Chase sequences are very important in horror movies and in horror literature.

134
00:09:17,880 --> 00:09:22,821
Having the protagonist of your story being hunted by something unknown or something scary,

135
00:09:23,121 --> 00:09:27,443
it resembles this feeling you have in nightmares when you're running but you're not going anywhere.

136
00:09:27,863 --> 00:09:30,403
So this is quite a strong emotion.

137
00:09:30,464 --> 00:09:33,725
So we knew we had to emulate this for our games somehow.

138
00:09:34,604 --> 00:09:39,048
First time we added it was in our first commercial project, Penumbra Overture.

139
00:09:39,688 --> 00:09:45,233
Turns out, 50% of the people that played it, okay, they liked it.

140
00:09:45,633 --> 00:09:49,796
50% that played it, the other half that is, they just hated it.

141
00:09:49,997 --> 00:09:55,701
So, you can ask yourselves, or we ask ourselves, what is the difference between these two groups?

142
00:09:55,861 --> 00:09:58,003
It turns out, the people that liked it...

143
00:09:59,299 --> 00:10:06,127
they've managed to complete these face sequences in one or two attempts.

144
00:10:06,147 --> 00:10:09,772
There are other people that took more tries and they didn't like it.

145
00:10:09,872 --> 00:10:13,576
So, the solution to fix this is really easy.

146
00:10:13,957 --> 00:10:18,262
You just don't make the player repeat it more than two times.

147
00:10:18,683 --> 00:10:25,111
In reality, this is not that easy of a design decision to make, because it means that you

148
00:10:25,171 --> 00:10:28,376
throw out the trial and error from your game.

149
00:10:29,097 --> 00:10:35,085
And trial and error is something that's seen as a good design choice in many situations.

150
00:10:36,086 --> 00:10:45,811
I remember speaking about this on the internet, and it was not uncommon for people to think when I spoke that you shouldn't have trial and error.

151
00:10:45,831 --> 00:10:49,273
They said, but trial and error is the ingredient in games.

152
00:10:49,733 --> 00:10:57,597
So I think it's fair to say that it's a wildly held belief that trial and error is a very important part of your games.

153
00:10:57,677 --> 00:11:00,459
And I admit to that, I thought this too.

154
00:11:01,319 --> 00:11:07,645
And so it shouldn't come as a surprise that when we did our Black Plague, which was the

155
00:11:07,805 --> 00:11:10,687
sequel to Penumbra Overture, we didn't fix the system.

156
00:11:10,727 --> 00:11:16,452
We have the same death mechanic, and from Niche our intent was to still have the same

157
00:11:17,073 --> 00:11:22,017
death mechanic that once you died you had to repeat the obstacle over and over again

158
00:11:22,037 --> 00:11:23,718
until you managed to overcome it.

159
00:11:25,321 --> 00:11:33,243
Now, it wasn't very late, until very late in development, half a year before Amnesia

160
00:11:33,283 --> 00:11:37,604
was to be completed, that we actually decided we shouldn't have any death.

161
00:11:37,644 --> 00:11:44,666
And this came about at the time when we thought about a lot of the design that we had in our

162
00:11:44,686 --> 00:11:44,906
game.

163
00:11:45,706 --> 00:11:54,290
The design that we chose to implement in our fake death system, or fake death system I should say,

164
00:11:54,650 --> 00:12:01,472
is that the player doesn't lose any progress when dying, but they're teleported somewhere else.

165
00:12:01,633 --> 00:12:05,334
And the important part is that we changed a little bit of the level.

166
00:12:07,035 --> 00:12:12,276
When the player had died, he woke up and didn't know what to expect this time around.

167
00:12:12,336 --> 00:12:19,778
And we thought that this fear of the unknown would be enough to make the player frightened of dying.

168
00:12:19,818 --> 00:12:25,200
And also on top of this, because we changed the map, we can add additional scares.

169
00:12:25,300 --> 00:12:29,121
So let's say the player walked through a hallway, and the first time around there weren't any

170
00:12:29,141 --> 00:12:32,262
monsters, then they died later up and then they had to walk through the hallway again.

171
00:12:32,282 --> 00:12:34,362
And then we can have some monster hiding around.

172
00:12:34,442 --> 00:12:38,927
I kept popping up through a corner this time, and that made a great effect because the player,

173
00:12:39,107 --> 00:12:42,370
you can have revitalized the section of the game.

174
00:12:42,390 --> 00:12:50,218
Now that we implemented it, it worked out way better than expected.

175
00:12:50,238 --> 00:12:56,865
Amnesia is filled with all these chase sequences, but yet nobody, as I know about, has complained

176
00:12:56,925 --> 00:12:58,246
about these chase sequences.

177
00:12:58,987 --> 00:13:01,669
And this is quite the thing.

178
00:13:01,969 --> 00:13:07,394
And even if they actually figured out the system, they figured out that if I die, it

179
00:13:07,434 --> 00:13:10,097
doesn't really matter, they still thought it was scary.

180
00:13:10,317 --> 00:13:15,802
Some people even thought it was scarier once they figured out that the system helped them

181
00:13:15,862 --> 00:13:19,886
along because they thought, okay, the game takes care of me, then I can focus on being

182
00:13:19,946 --> 00:13:22,208
immersed in the game instead.

183
00:13:23,269 --> 00:13:28,032
Keep in mind that this system could really easily be exploited.

184
00:13:28,292 --> 00:13:33,335
So, let's say the player faces an enemy, it can just run up against it and die each time

185
00:13:33,375 --> 00:13:37,037
and eventually they would manage to overcome the obstacle.

186
00:13:37,277 --> 00:13:39,378
But yet, pretty much no one did this.

187
00:13:39,679 --> 00:13:45,542
And I think this is amazing, considering how slapped on and rushed this sort of mechanic was.

188
00:13:45,923 --> 00:13:47,063
It wasn't until the half...

189
00:13:47,764 --> 00:13:52,127
last half year that we implemented this and we had tons of other stuff to do at that time.

190
00:13:52,468 --> 00:13:57,112
So the events we added and the changes we made, they were all quite rushed.

191
00:13:58,453 --> 00:14:03,377
Now on to the final design principle, no competitive mechanics.

192
00:14:04,044 --> 00:14:11,107
What I mean by no competitive mechanics is game systems that instead of setting up challenges

193
00:14:11,127 --> 00:14:17,709
that the player needs to complete, works along with the player and auto-corrects itself according

194
00:14:17,749 --> 00:14:22,390
to the player's play style or just doesn't really affect the gameplay in any way.

195
00:14:23,931 --> 00:14:33,395
And this choice has its base in our sanity mechanic, and the sanity mechanic has its base in that very early on in the project.

196
00:14:33,715 --> 00:14:36,496
We knew that we wanted the player to be afraid of the dark somehow.

197
00:14:36,536 --> 00:14:42,158
We knew that if he stayed in the dark he should be penetralized with something, so he should really fear the darkness.

198
00:14:42,819 --> 00:14:45,940
And we first thought, OK, let's lower the player's health.

199
00:14:47,321 --> 00:14:49,242
That doesn't really feel right.

200
00:14:49,342 --> 00:14:52,363
So we added a sanity system instead.

201
00:14:52,864 --> 00:14:56,145
We also extended this sanity system

202
00:14:56,285 --> 00:14:59,007
to monsters and other sites instead.

203
00:14:59,027 --> 00:15:02,609
And we added also for penalties to this.

204
00:15:02,989 --> 00:15:06,031
For example, if the player's walk speed,

205
00:15:06,151 --> 00:15:08,012
if it's insane, would be lower,

206
00:15:08,212 --> 00:15:12,174
or enemies would have easier to spot the player

207
00:15:12,234 --> 00:15:15,536
if he was insane, and then eventually the player would die.

208
00:15:16,156 --> 00:15:22,524
And so, with all these penalties in and we thought that, okay, the player will not want to be insane in our game,

209
00:15:22,784 --> 00:15:25,187
we just had to balance it.

210
00:15:25,387 --> 00:15:31,033
Now, this turns out, balancing this sort of system ain't very easy.

211
00:15:31,874 --> 00:15:37,442
Instead, there's lots of things to consider with this kind of balancing.

212
00:15:38,283 --> 00:15:39,684
How many tinderboxes?

213
00:15:39,704 --> 00:15:43,690
These are the resources the players use to light up the environment.

214
00:15:43,730 --> 00:15:45,412
How many of those have the player collected?

215
00:15:45,672 --> 00:15:47,915
How fast do they move through our levels?

216
00:15:48,516 --> 00:15:48,616
And...

217
00:15:49,637 --> 00:15:53,319
how good is the spare on their lamp oil and so on.

218
00:15:53,679 --> 00:15:57,781
On top of this, the sanity system doesn't really reset itself,

219
00:15:57,922 --> 00:16:01,904
so something that you do, not pick up enough tinderboxes at the start of the game,

220
00:16:02,164 --> 00:16:04,425
can have repercussions at the end of the game.

221
00:16:04,625 --> 00:16:07,787
So, if we didn't find the system balanced,

222
00:16:07,867 --> 00:16:12,369
what we had to do was to replay the game several times,

223
00:16:12,609 --> 00:16:15,290
using different playstyles, every time we made a change.

224
00:16:15,711 --> 00:16:17,211
It just wasn't workable.

225
00:16:17,592 --> 00:16:24,477
So it led to the design choice that was quite drastic, that okay, we shouldn't have any

226
00:16:24,537 --> 00:16:27,880
penalties, we shouldn't have any gaming aspects to the sanity system.

227
00:16:28,300 --> 00:16:31,242
Instead, we thought it more as a mood feature.

228
00:16:31,763 --> 00:16:36,727
We just, the game system just keeps the balance.

229
00:16:38,888 --> 00:16:41,169
moves along in the same way that the player does.

230
00:16:41,229 --> 00:16:42,590
It auto-adapts itself.

231
00:16:43,210 --> 00:16:45,691
And once we had this kind of system in,

232
00:16:45,751 --> 00:16:47,171
instead of auto-adapting itself,

233
00:16:47,271 --> 00:16:48,772
all of the problems disappeared.

234
00:16:49,152 --> 00:16:53,634
Plus, players were more immersed in this kind of system.

235
00:16:54,654 --> 00:16:56,375
Because they didn't have to beat it,

236
00:16:56,435 --> 00:16:59,076
so they can just role-play in it instead.

237
00:16:59,116 --> 00:17:01,677
And this kind of auto-correction,

238
00:17:01,797 --> 00:17:05,179
it just also spurred the imagination of the players.

239
00:17:06,299 --> 00:17:09,742
roleplayed, what was happening to them and so on.

240
00:17:09,762 --> 00:17:14,766
And worth noting is that just as the no-death mechanic,

241
00:17:15,326 --> 00:17:18,328
even if the players figured out how the system worked,

242
00:17:18,649 --> 00:17:21,771
most players were scared anyway and were immersed in it,

243
00:17:21,911 --> 00:17:25,934
and some players were scared even more when they realized this.

244
00:17:26,595 --> 00:17:29,317
We applied this kind of thinking to our enemies instead.

245
00:17:29,377 --> 00:17:32,459
So we said, OK, instead of having them as a challenge,

246
00:17:32,519 --> 00:17:35,881
all these enemies, let's have them as a part

247
00:17:35,921 --> 00:17:37,122
of the atmosphere instead.

248
00:17:37,842 --> 00:17:39,683
And the way we went about with this

249
00:17:39,763 --> 00:17:43,306
is consider the players looking at an enemy.

250
00:17:43,826 --> 00:17:49,191
And he has to hide, and then he has to go in hiding in a corner in the oppressive darkness,

251
00:17:49,231 --> 00:17:54,036
his sanity is draining, and the enemy comes lurking and sniffing around,

252
00:17:54,617 --> 00:17:57,039
trying to find the player, and the player sits there, he asks,

253
00:17:57,139 --> 00:18:00,562
oh will he go away? And then the enemy comes really close,

254
00:18:00,622 --> 00:18:04,606
and then he walks away just in time, and the player is just...

255
00:18:05,127 --> 00:18:07,988
finally he didn't spot me and then he can sneak up and

256
00:18:09,308 --> 00:18:15,971
is he still there and so on, having all these thoughts, but what really happened in the AI was that

257
00:18:16,411 --> 00:18:19,293
AI knew in a way where the player was and he was

258
00:18:19,653 --> 00:18:23,254
okay I'm gonna just get really close to the player and

259
00:18:23,574 --> 00:18:25,935
not near enough so he's really spooked

260
00:18:26,316 --> 00:18:30,637
and then I'm just gonna walk off and if he just sits still and doesn't run away and

261
00:18:30,677 --> 00:18:34,499
try to play a hero, which is changing the play style, he will be okay.

262
00:18:34,979 --> 00:18:40,322
And this sort of system, it creates these really tense moments that feel scripted,

263
00:18:40,562 --> 00:18:43,283
but they come out of the dynamics of the system.

264
00:18:43,523 --> 00:18:48,985
If we would have had a more competitive system that was supposed to challenge the player,

265
00:18:49,405 --> 00:18:53,287
having this sort of response would have been a lot harder,

266
00:18:53,307 --> 00:18:58,809
and it would have been a lot harder to have it consistently reproduced as well.

267
00:18:58,869 --> 00:19:03,531
I'm just going to list the different things I've gone through, so we have no weapons.

268
00:19:04,052 --> 00:19:06,974
and no death, and no competitive mechanics.

269
00:19:07,434 --> 00:19:13,378
With this stuff I'm just going to give a little taste what we accomplished by these things.

270
