00:19:38,006 --> 00:19:40,028
I'm going to need a hand.

275
00:19:40,269 --> 00:19:40,969
Oh shit!

276
00:19:42,751 --> 00:19:43,612
Oh fuck.

277
00:19:45,073 --> 00:19:47,015
Oh shit, I can see the thing!

278
00:19:47,496 --> 00:19:48,076
I can see it!

279
00:19:50,579 --> 00:19:50,959
Oh no.

280
00:19:51,239 --> 00:19:51,580
No!

281
00:19:52,220 --> 00:19:52,501
No!

282
00:19:53,041 --> 00:19:54,302
It's coming!

283
00:19:54,382 --> 00:19:54,823
It's gonna-

284
00:20:32,919 --> 00:20:36,700
loneliness is probably the scariest thing I've seen so

285
00:20:36,801 --> 00:20:40,142
i'm not sure if this makes me a little bit

286
00:20:58,889 --> 00:21:03,895
So, I'm not sure if this makes me depraved, but I'm really pleased to see that kind of reaction.

287
00:21:05,177 --> 00:21:09,103
So, this reaction, it's quite strong, but it's not a unique moment.

288
00:21:09,163 --> 00:21:13,829
If you search YouTube for amnesia reaction, you will see tons of this kind of stuff.

289
00:21:15,371 --> 00:21:19,615
I want to note again, these principles that we implemented, they were quite rushed.

290
00:21:19,635 --> 00:21:21,456
They were at the end of the project.

291
00:21:21,496 --> 00:21:26,760
The no-death mechanic and the no-competitive mechanics were at the very end of when we

292
00:21:26,800 --> 00:21:29,543
tried to fix everything else, it was rushed.

293
00:21:30,964 --> 00:21:35,527
So I believe there's tons more to explore with this kind of stuff.

294
00:21:35,607 --> 00:21:39,190
And this leads me to the next part of this talk.

295
00:21:40,151 --> 00:21:46,693
which I will go dig a little bit deeper into it and now it's time for three general principles.

296
00:21:47,813 --> 00:21:54,035
Now the no combat thing, what I think this boils down to is that we should be a little

297
00:21:54,055 --> 00:21:57,596
bit careful about finding fun fillers for our games.

298
00:21:58,036 --> 00:22:04,598
Fun fillers is something that I think is a gameplay mechanic that once implemented you

299
00:22:04,638 --> 00:22:06,598
can have lots and lots of gameplay with it.

300
00:22:07,318 --> 00:22:10,419
And stuff like this is, of course, combat.

301
00:22:10,479 --> 00:22:12,739
It's used in pretty much every game.

302
00:22:12,799 --> 00:22:16,900
And I think the reason for it, it's so hard to come up

303
00:22:16,940 --> 00:22:19,461
with other interesting ways of interacting

304
00:22:19,521 --> 00:22:22,421
with our virtual world, so we do it with combat.

305
00:22:22,441 --> 00:22:24,581
So instead of figuring out some system

306
00:22:24,641 --> 00:22:27,242
that can consistently be used in a way

307
00:22:27,322 --> 00:22:29,542
to move along with the narrative,

308
00:22:29,582 --> 00:22:32,943
you just want to drop a bunch of enemies into a room

309
00:22:32,983 --> 00:22:35,263
and then place the player there and have them fight them.

310
00:22:36,244 --> 00:22:42,008
This is why the lure of the combat is so strong and we have been tempted ourselves as well.

311
00:22:42,548 --> 00:22:47,392
But as we have seen, once we remove the combat, new horizons open up.

312
00:22:47,552 --> 00:22:54,658
Once we remove that weapon that bobs in front of the screen, players start to approach the

313
00:22:54,678 --> 00:22:55,819
game quite differently.

314
00:22:55,939 --> 00:22:58,921
And I think there are three major reasons for this.

315
00:22:59,522 --> 00:23:02,964
The first off is the myth of multitasking.

316
00:23:03,004 --> 00:23:11,809
We like to believe our brains are these big parallel computers that can take in input from all over the place and process it all simultaneously.

317
00:23:11,889 --> 00:23:18,252
So at the lower circuitry level our brains are big parallel computers, but at the higher level it just doesn't work that way.

318
00:23:18,272 --> 00:23:22,154
Instead they are like in techy speak, like single core computers.

319
00:23:23,895 --> 00:23:26,336
two things that you want to do at the same time.

320
00:23:26,816 --> 00:23:28,516
You have to switch between them.

321
00:23:28,877 --> 00:23:30,937
And every switch means an overhead.

322
00:23:31,417 --> 00:23:37,259
And this overhead means that you lose some sort of time when you're doing something.

323
00:23:37,279 --> 00:23:41,560
So this is the reason why you don't want to talk on a cell phone while driving.

324
00:23:41,600 --> 00:23:47,421
Or if you're watching cat clips on YouTube while I'm giving this lecture, you might not

325
00:23:47,481 --> 00:23:49,721
get every word that I'm saying.

326
00:23:52,244 --> 00:23:56,066
Okay, everyone get that? So, let's move on here.

327
00:23:58,327 --> 00:24:04,911
Now, this of course has impact on our games. If we have a game that's about combat,

328
00:24:04,931 --> 00:24:07,232
then you have other elements in the game as well.

329
00:24:07,772 --> 00:24:13,315
If the player chooses to focus on these other elements, they will be worse at the combat.

330
00:24:13,695 --> 00:24:19,257
So, if the combat has a competitive element to it, meaning that if you're good at it,

331
00:24:19,337 --> 00:24:22,337
it's easier to progress and you get more out of the game.

332
00:24:22,778 --> 00:24:27,739
If you have an audio log popping up from somewhere while the player is shooting off enemies,

333
00:24:27,779 --> 00:24:32,300
they will just push that audio log aside and keep shooting at the enemies because that's

334
00:24:32,340 --> 00:24:33,620
what the game is about.

335
00:24:34,100 --> 00:24:38,941
And there doesn't even have to be enemies on screen while you're...

336
00:24:39,902 --> 00:24:47,923
because this effect is set in, they can just have the threat of having enemies and the focus will be off from other things instead.

337
00:24:49,004 --> 00:24:56,445
But if you remove this, clear your head and the player is free to focus on other things instead.

338
00:24:56,505 --> 00:25:02,067
And when we made this switch from Penumbra Overture to Black Plague, where Black Plague didn't have combat,

339
00:25:02,407 --> 00:25:04,447
it was quite obvious this change.

340
00:25:05,027 --> 00:25:11,889
Now, the second reason for not having combat is that the tools we give to the player, they

341
00:25:11,989 --> 00:25:14,870
tell them what role they have in our games.

342
00:25:15,391 --> 00:25:20,232
So if you give the player a gun, he will expect to go to a shooting range.

343
00:25:20,612 --> 00:25:25,757
Now, this is partly because of condition. We've learned to play games in this way in the past.

344
00:25:26,077 --> 00:25:31,001
But it's also that once you have a specific tool for the player, an interaction,

345
00:25:31,381 --> 00:25:34,003
it will tell the player what role they play.

346
00:25:34,244 --> 00:25:36,585
The way they interact with the world...

347
00:25:37,426 --> 00:25:41,611
the changes or defines the way the player is.

348
00:25:41,811 --> 00:25:45,555
So, if we want to, for example, have the player

349
00:25:45,575 --> 00:25:47,857
that's a detective, we need to make sure

350
00:25:47,917 --> 00:25:50,160
that the interactions we have in our game

351
00:25:50,500 --> 00:25:52,802
supports this role of the player.

352
00:25:53,463 --> 00:25:55,946
So, if we want to have different.

353
00:25:56,426 --> 00:26:02,469
expressive in games, we need to make sure that the interaction supports these expressions.

354
00:26:02,529 --> 00:26:07,991
The larger part an interaction has in a game, the larger part it will form the way the players

355
00:26:08,051 --> 00:26:08,891
see themselves.

356
00:26:10,969 --> 00:26:16,514
And I think it was Tim Schafer that said that he realised how psychopaths must feel.

357
00:26:16,534 --> 00:26:22,919
The only way they can express themselves is with a gun, so all people they meet they just shoot at.

358
00:26:22,940 --> 00:26:27,664
And if we want to have different experiences, we need to have different sorts of interaction.

359
00:26:28,304 --> 00:26:33,349
Once we remove weapons, we force the player into expressing themselves in different ways.

360
00:26:34,870 --> 00:26:39,314
The third reason is density of information flow.

361
00:26:39,654 --> 00:26:46,540
I like to liken amnesia to a sort of sensory deprivation chamber.

362
00:26:47,301 --> 00:26:52,605
Once the player is in the game, they start to focus all on this small stuff

363
00:26:52,665 --> 00:26:56,188
that they, in a combat game, wouldn't notice at all.

364
00:26:57,369 --> 00:27:01,471
For example, if a small sound or a quiet sound is playing,

365
00:27:01,511 --> 00:27:04,532
they will give lots of thought to this sound.

366
00:27:04,552 --> 00:27:06,413
So if they hear some creaking in the corridor,

367
00:27:06,473 --> 00:27:08,494
they will start thinking, what was that noise?

368
00:27:09,574 --> 00:27:12,115
Could it have been a creature stalking me?

369
00:27:12,755 --> 00:27:13,476
Oh, I'm hunted.

370
00:27:13,676 --> 00:27:14,376
I need to hide.

371
00:27:14,436 --> 00:27:16,617
And this is just from a little sound.

372
00:27:16,677 --> 00:27:19,918
And when watching videos of people playing our game,

373
00:27:20,879 --> 00:27:23,660
we see this vast difference from other games

374
00:27:23,740 --> 00:27:26,101
that have much more action focus.

375
00:27:26,912 --> 00:27:34,195
Now, the downside of having this sort of approach is that it's much harder to design it.

376
00:27:34,575 --> 00:27:39,637
As a designer, you know every nook and cranny of the levels that you're designing.

377
00:27:39,977 --> 00:27:43,798
So when you're trying to put yourself in the place of a first-time player...

378
00:27:44,779 --> 00:27:49,981
you won't, it will be very hard to emulate the kind of experience they're going to have.

379
00:27:50,001 --> 00:27:53,403
An example of this is this map in Amnesia.

380
00:27:53,983 --> 00:27:57,745
We were sure that it would be really boring when we talked about it and said,

381
00:27:58,045 --> 00:28:01,826
oh, there's not enough events, it's not going to be very frightening,

382
00:28:01,846 --> 00:28:04,868
the player's going to be bored out of their skulls when playing this.

383
00:28:05,428 --> 00:28:09,290
Then it turns out, when they played it, they were more than enough engaged,

384
00:28:09,310 --> 00:28:14,012
they thought that it was really thrilling, this level, and we had no idea about this.

385
00:28:14,573 --> 00:28:19,999
So, because of this hardness, I think it might not be tempting to have this sort of design

386
00:28:20,019 --> 00:28:21,902
because it's very hard to try it out.

387
00:28:21,982 --> 00:28:27,328
But I mean, this is a new thing and the more we can design levels in this way, the more

388
00:28:27,368 --> 00:28:27,969
we learn it.

389
00:28:28,049 --> 00:28:31,693
And I think it can become much more intuitive than it was for us.

390
00:28:33,976 --> 00:28:45,785
A really great example of this loss of information, or of smaller information density, comes from the blog which is called Awesome X Machinima.

391
00:28:46,346 --> 00:28:51,149
And the writer there, he tries to play GTA IV as a law-abiding citizen.

392
00:28:51,209 --> 00:28:53,411
And here's what he writes about it, some snippets.

393
00:28:54,105 --> 00:28:59,630
Walking the streets, I heard near hours of conversations, insults and quips from the

394
00:28:59,670 --> 00:29:04,314
civilians walking the streets that I had never heard, things I certainly would have missed

395
00:29:04,414 --> 00:29:08,477
careering down the streets at top speed and shooting back at the cops in pursuit of me.

396
00:29:09,158 --> 00:29:13,382
I saw billboards I never knew existed, buildings I had no idea I could enter.

397
00:29:13,622 --> 00:29:18,246
I watched a man on a bench flip through a fully rendered pages of an actual book, a

398
00:29:18,306 --> 00:29:22,670
store owner meticulously clean a sidewalk, and watched a police officer place someone

399
00:29:22,710 --> 00:29:25,593
in the back of his cruiser after an elaborate fruit pursuit.

400
00:29:26,413 --> 00:29:27,534
Later down he writes this.

401
00:29:28,115 --> 00:29:32,961
Rather than the poor for the course, every infraction, no matter how slight,

402
00:29:33,321 --> 00:29:35,383
becomes a thrilling crescendo moment.

403
00:29:35,704 --> 00:29:39,048
This made the missions themselves a nerve-wracking experience.

404
00:29:39,408 --> 00:29:44,454
And I just think this greatly shows the new kind of frontiers this opens up

405
00:29:44,534 --> 00:29:45,976
with this sort of thinking.

406
00:29:46,937 --> 00:29:50,558
Now, the next lesson is no proper death.

407
00:29:51,078 --> 00:30:00,202
The lesson I think here from this design principle is that we should really carefully consider if trial and error is something that we want in our games.

408
00:30:00,302 --> 00:30:04,103
Now, obviously some games thrive on trial and error.

409
00:30:04,123 --> 00:30:06,184
I'm not saying that these games should throw them out.

410
00:30:06,284 --> 00:30:07,644
But if you have a game...

411
00:30:08,265 --> 00:30:12,308
where the player is supposed to be present in our virtual worlds,

412
00:30:12,609 --> 00:30:13,689
we need to consider,

413
00:30:13,990 --> 00:30:19,374
do we really want the player to be stuck in an endless loop

414
00:30:19,434 --> 00:30:22,917
or be forced to repeat things over and over again?

415
00:30:22,957 --> 00:30:27,441
And there are three main reasons why we do not want to do it,

416
00:30:27,521 --> 00:30:28,462
at least I think there is.

417
00:30:29,063 --> 00:30:32,025
First of all, hard to repeat moments.

418
00:30:32,045 --> 00:30:34,047
And I think this is the most important one.

419
00:30:35,048 --> 00:30:38,450
An obvious example, as I've mentioned before, are the chase sequences.

420
00:30:38,510 --> 00:30:42,092
When you repeat them too many times, they just weren't tense anymore.

421
00:30:42,352 --> 00:30:43,893
But there are other examples as well.

422
00:30:44,474 --> 00:30:50,878
Sad scenes, scenes that are boring but set the mood, or scenes that are just sensory

423
00:30:50,938 --> 00:30:51,618
demanding.

424
00:30:51,998 --> 00:30:54,580
Other media, they thrive on these sort of things.

425
00:30:55,160 --> 00:31:00,528
But they're almost absent from actual gameplay, not cutscenes that is in our games.

426
00:31:00,628 --> 00:31:07,117
And I think that we might actually or probably missing out on a lot of things if the only

427
00:31:07,177 --> 00:31:11,944
thing that we want in our games are situations that are easily repeated.

428
00:31:12,785 --> 00:31:18,889
The next reason is that once you repeat something over and over, you start to see below this,

429
00:31:18,929 --> 00:31:21,211
you start to see the mechanics, how it all works.

430
00:31:21,591 --> 00:31:27,535
And having trial and error not only makes this possible, it might even force this behaviour.

431
00:31:27,615 --> 00:31:30,057
If you have something that the player needs to overcome,

432
00:31:30,657 --> 00:31:35,280
and the player, in order to progress, he needs to figure this out, he needs to overcome it.

433
00:31:36,601 --> 00:31:41,503
the player is forced into thinking how does this system really works and the way they do it is that

434
00:31:41,543 --> 00:31:46,004
they ship away on their own make-belief and they're taking themselves out of the immersion

435
00:31:46,244 --> 00:31:52,366
the more times to repeat it and I'm not sure if that's something that we want in our game

436
00:31:53,267 --> 00:31:56,428
making the players feel unimmersed by the game mechanics.

437
00:31:57,968 --> 00:32:04,274
Now, the last and perhaps more evident reason is just the flow of the player's narrative.

438
00:32:04,755 --> 00:32:13,082
Do we really want players to repeat sections? Is that a good part of the narrative we want to bring to the player?

439
00:32:14,623 --> 00:32:19,988
I think this is a very important part, but some people might say, okay, but if we just

440
00:32:20,068 --> 00:32:26,233
let the player play through all this without no obstacles, there will be no tension.

441
00:32:26,573 --> 00:32:32,057
But if a horror game as Amnesia cannot have any trial and error and still manages to be

442
00:32:32,077 --> 00:32:37,662
scary, perhaps even more scary, I'm not seeing why this shouldn't be possible for other games

443
00:32:37,762 --> 00:32:40,524
as well that aren't horror games.

444
00:32:41,145 --> 00:32:47,671
Now, last design principle. This is the no competitive mechanic that we used for the sanity in AI.

445
00:32:48,111 --> 00:32:52,595
And what we learned from this is once we removed the competitive aspect,

446
00:32:53,116 --> 00:32:57,580
forced the player into overcoming these goals and trying to beat the system,

447
00:32:57,880 --> 00:33:02,204
we got a better response and it was much easier to consistently...

448
00:33:03,405 --> 00:33:05,549
replicate the behaviors that we wanted.

449
00:33:06,730 --> 00:33:12,380
What it did was that it allowed role-playing instead of the player optimizing a system.

450
00:33:12,420 --> 00:33:15,224
Now, what I mean by optimizing a system is that

451
00:33:17,047 --> 00:33:24,276
Normally what the player does with this interaction once it's competitive is that it changes the game's stats in some way.

452
00:33:24,296 --> 00:33:28,020
So for example, you say the player is faced with two enemies.

453
00:33:28,381 --> 00:33:35,870
Now he has to make a choice here, what to do, and it depends on, okay, what weapons do I have at hand, and how much ammo do I have for each weapon.

454
00:33:36,450 --> 00:33:40,933
What are these enemies? What kind of stats do I know they have? What weaknesses do they have?

455
00:33:41,293 --> 00:33:46,015
And what might I meet at the road ahead? And so on and so forth.

456
00:33:46,075 --> 00:33:49,037
Now, the player can choose, okay, I'm just going to do what's fun.

457
00:33:49,157 --> 00:33:52,298
But that's not mostly what happens.

458
00:33:52,358 --> 00:33:59,082
What happens is that the player tries to do what is best for them game stats or game mechanically-wise.

459
00:33:59,122 --> 00:34:04,224
And they try to have bad things happening to themselves. They try to avoid that.

460
00:34:04,945 --> 00:34:12,451
And what this does is that it forces the players into a certain behavior controlled by the game mechanics.

461
00:34:13,592 --> 00:34:18,736
Now, imagine having this sort of optimizing system, or optimizing experience,

462
00:34:18,836 --> 00:34:22,759
for something that is supposed to elicit emotions from the player,

463
00:34:22,819 --> 00:34:24,641
like simulating a relationship.

464
00:34:24,661 --> 00:34:27,984
Say we have a character that constantly follows the player around.

465
00:34:28,744 --> 00:34:31,766
we might come to a situation where the player stands between,

466
00:34:31,826 --> 00:34:35,930
okay, either I'm going to do what my feelings tell me to do,

467
00:34:35,950 --> 00:34:39,292
or I'm going to do what's best for me gameplay-wise.

468
00:34:39,832 --> 00:34:42,935
Now, this might, of course, be interesting,

469
00:34:43,055 --> 00:34:46,057
but what I think mostly happens is that the player will just,

470
00:34:46,117 --> 00:34:48,519
okay, I'm just going to do what's best for me gameplay-wise,

471
00:34:48,559 --> 00:34:51,821
let's screw the feelings here, I want to progress later in the game.

472
00:34:52,102 --> 00:34:55,484
And if you have a system that have repercussions over a long time,

473
00:34:55,885 --> 00:34:57,446
like we know our relationship has,

474
00:34:57,806 --> 00:34:58,547
then, I mean the...

475
00:34:58,647 --> 00:35:03,831
player is not going to want to jeopardize their gameplay later on in the game.

476
00:35:03,851 --> 00:35:08,035
They're not sure what's going to happen for them later on.

477
00:35:08,696 --> 00:35:14,561
And this is why I think that if we want to do something like this, we need to remove

478
00:35:14,581 --> 00:35:15,642
the competitive aspect.

479
00:35:15,662 --> 00:35:21,707
We need to see this sort of mechanics as something that just brings more to the experience.

